e Institute for Advanced Study Computer -- t3. Automata Theory and Logic Machines -- t4. Numerical Mathematics -- t5. Nun~ericalM eteorology -- t6. Engineering Activities and Achievements -- t7. The Computer and UNESCO -- t8. The Early Industrial Scene -- t9. Programming Languages -- t10. Conclusions -- tAPPENDIX: World-Wide Developments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1942, Lt. Herman H. Goldstine, a former mathematics professor, was stationed at the Moore School of Electrical Engineering at the University of Pennsylvania. It was there that he assisted in the creation of the ENIAC, the first electronic digital computer. The ENIAC was operational in 1945, but plans for a new computer were already underway. The principal source of ideas for the new computer was John von Neumann, who became Goldstine's chief collaborator. Together they developed EDVAC, successor to ENIAC. After World War II, at the Institute for Advanced Study, they built what was to become the prototype of the present-day computer. Herman Goldstine writes as both historian and scientist in this first examination of the development of computing machinery, from the seventeenth century through the early 1950s. His personal involvement lends a special authenticity to his narrative, as he sprinkles anecdotes and stories liberally through his text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082013940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400820139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400820139.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-199